[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-array] This section provides some examples of common array operations in JavaScript.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-array] This example shows three ways to create new array: first using array literal notation, then using the `Array()` constructor, and finally using `String.prototype.split()` to build the array from a string.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-array] This example uses the `join()` method to create a string from the `fruits` array.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-array] This example shows how to access items in the `fruits` array by specifying the index number of their position in the array.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-array] This example uses the `indexOf()` method to find the position (index) of the string `"Banana"` in the `fruits` array.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-array] This example shows two ways to check if the `fruits` array contains `"Banana"` and `"Cherry"`: first with the `includes()` method, and then with the `indexOf()` method to test for an index value that's not `-1`.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-array] This example uses the `push()` method to append a new string to the `fruits` array.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-array] This example uses the `pop()` method to remove the last item from the `fruits` array.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-array] This example uses the `splice()` method to remove the last 3 items from the `fruits` array.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-array] This example uses the `splice()` method to truncate the `fruits` array down to just its first 2 items.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-array] This example uses the `shift()` method to remove the first item from the `fruits` array.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-array] This example uses the `splice()` method to remove the first 3 items from the `fruits` array.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-array] This example uses the `unshift()` method to add, at index `0`, a new item to the `fruits` array — making it the new first item in the array.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-array] This example uses the `splice()` method to remove the string `"Banana"` from the `fruits` array — by specifying the index position of `"Banana"`.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-array] This example uses the `splice()` method to remove the strings `"Banana"` and `"Strawberry"` from the `fruits` array — by specifying the index position of `"Banana"`, along with a count of the number of total items to remove.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-array] This example uses the `splice()` method to replace the last 2 items in the `fruits` array with new items.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-array] This example uses a `for...of` loop to iterate over the `fruits` array, logging each item to the console.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-array] But `for...of` is just one of many ways to iterate over any array; for more ways, see Loops and iteration, and see the documentation for the `every()`, `filter()`, `flatMap()`, `map()`, `reduce()`, and `reduceRight()` methods — and see the next example, which uses the `forEach()` method.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-array] This example uses the `forEach()` method to call a function on each element in the `fruits` array; the function causes each item to be logged to the console, along with the item's index number.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-array] This example uses the `concat()` method to merge the `fruits` array with a `moreFruits` array, to produce a new `combinedFruits` array.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-array] Notice that `fruits` and `moreFruits` remain unchanged.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-array] This example shows three ways to create a new array from the existing `fruits` array: first by using spread syntax, then by using the `from()` method, and then by using the `slice()` method.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-array] All built-in array-copy operations (spread syntax, `Array.from()`, `Array.prototype.slice()`, and `Array.prototype.concat()`) create shallow copies.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-array] If you instead want a deep copy of an array, you can use `JSON.stringify()` to convert the array to a JSON string, and then `JSON.parse()` to convert the string back into a new array that's completely independent from the original array.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-array] You can also create deep copies using the `structuredClone()` method, which has the advantage of allowing transferable objects in the source to be *transferred* to the new copy, rather than just cloned.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-array] Finally, it's important to understand that assigning an existing array to a new variable doesn't create a copy of either the array or its elements.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-array] Instead the new variable is just a reference, or alias, to the original array; that is, the original array's name and the new variable name are just two names for the exact same object (and so will always evaluate as strictly equivalent).
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-array] The following creates a chessboard as a two-dimensional array of strings.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-array] The first move is made by copying the `'p'` in `board[6][4]` to `board[4][4]`.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-array] The old position at `[6][4]` is made blank.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-array] The result of a match between a `RegExp` and a string can create a JavaScript array that has properties and elements which provide information about the match.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-array] Such an array is returned by `RegExp.prototype.exec()` and `String.prototype.match()`.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-array] For more information about the result of a match, see the `RegExp.prototype.exec()` and `String.prototype.match()` pages.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-array] Iterative methods do not mutate the array on which it is called, but the function provided as `callbackFn` can.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-array] The key principle to remember is that only indexes between 0 and `arrayLength - 1` are visited, where `arrayLength` is the length of the array at the time the array method was first called, but the element passed to the callback is the value at the time the index is visited.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-array] The following examples use the `forEach` method as an example, but other methods that visit indexes in ascending order work in the same way.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-array] Inserting *n* elements at unvisited indexes that are less than the initial array length will make them be visited.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-array] Deleting *n* elements at unvisited indexes will make them not be visited anymore.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-array] Because the array has shrunk, the last *n* iterations will visit out-of-bounds indexes.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-array] Deleting *n* elements at already visited indexes does not change the fact that they were visited before they get deleted.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-array] Because the array has shrunk, the next *n* elements after the current index are skipped.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-array] For methods that iterate in descending order of index, insertion causes elements to be skipped, and deletion causes elements to be visited multiple times.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-array] Adjust the code above yourself to see the effects.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-object] The **`Object`** type represents one of JavaScript's data types.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-object] It is used to store various keyed collections and more complex entities.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-object] Objects can be created using the `Object()` constructor or the object initializer / literal syntax.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-object] Nearly all objects in JavaScript are instances of `Object`; a typical object inherits properties (including methods) from `Object.prototype`, although these properties may be shadowed (a.k.a. overridden).
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-object] The only objects that don't inherit from `Object.prototype` are those with `null` prototype, or descended from other `null` prototype objects.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-object] Changes to the `Object.prototype` object are seen by **all** objects through prototype chaining, unless the properties and methods subject to those changes are overridden further along the prototype chain.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-object] This provides a very powerful although potentially dangerous mechanism to override or extend object behavior.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-object] To make it more secure, `Object.prototype` is the only object in the core JavaScript language that has immutable prototype — the prototype of `Object.prototype` is always `null` and not changeable.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-object] You should avoid calling any of the `Object.prototype` methods directly from the instance, especially those that are not intended to be polymorphic (i.e., only its initial behavior makes sense and no descending object could override it in a meaningful way).
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-object] All objects descending from `Object.prototype` may define a custom own property that has the same name, but with entirely different semantics from what you expect.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-object] Furthermore, these properties are not inherited by `null`-prototype objects.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-object] All modern JavaScript utilities for working with objects are static.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-object] There isn't any method in an Object itself to delete its own properties (such as `Map.prototype.delete()`).
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-object] To do so, one must use the `delete` operator.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-object] Almost all objects in JavaScript ultimately inherit from `Object.prototype` (see inheritance and the prototype chain).
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-object] However, you may create `null`-prototype objects using `Object.create(null)` or the object initializer syntax with `__proto__: null` (note: the `__proto__` key in object literals is different from the deprecated `Object.prototype.__proto__` property).
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-object] You can also change the prototype of an existing object to `null` by calling `Object.setPrototypeOf(obj, null)`.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-object] An object with a `null` prototype can behave in unexpected ways, because it doesn't inherit any object methods from `Object.prototype`.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-object] This is especially true when debugging, since common object-property converting/detecting utility functions may generate errors, or lose information (especially if using silent error-traps that ignore errors).
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-object] Unlike normal objects, in which `toString()` is on the object's prototype, the `toString()` method here is an own property of `nullProtoObj`.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-object] This is because `nullProtoObj` has no (`null`) prototype.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-object] You can also revert a null-prototype object back to an ordinary object using `Object.setPrototypeOf(nullProtoObj, Object.prototype)`.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-object] In practice, objects with `null` prototype are usually used as a cheap substitute for maps.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-object] In such case, the addition of any method should be done cautiously, as they can be confused with the other key-value pairs stored as data.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-object] Making your object not inherit from `Object.prototype` also prevents prototype pollution attacks.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-object] If a malicious script adds a property to `Object.prototype`, it will be accessible on every object in your program, except objects that have null prototype.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-object] JavaScript also has built-in APIs that produce `null`-prototype objects, especially those that use objects as ad hoc key-value collections.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-object] The term "`null`-prototype object" often also includes any object without `Object.prototype` in its prototype chain.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-object] Such objects can be created with `extends null` when using classes.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-object] Many built-in operations that expect objects first coerce their arguments to objects.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-object] There are two ways to achieve nearly the same effect in JavaScript.
[src:lodash-utils/global-objects-object] Unlike conversion to primitives, the object coercion process itself is not observable in any way, since it doesn't invoke custom code like `toString` or `valueOf` methods.
